> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PEEBT756 - ADVANCED COMPUTER PROGRAMMING TECHNIQUES
> - **Module:** Module 2
> - **Topic:** Shape Package

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In the context of the **KTU 2024 Scheme (PEEBT756)**, the **Shape Package** is a modular, namespace-bound software engineering construct used in **Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)** to logically group related classes, interfaces, enumerations, and exception types that represent geometric figures (2D and 3D shapes) under a single, encapsulated container.

According to the **2024 NEP-aligned syllabus**, a Shape Package typically embodies the following Pillar Concepts of OOP:

- **Abstraction** (via abstract classes or interfaces)
- **Encapsulation** (private data members with public getters/setters)
- **Inheritance** (a base `Shape` class extended by `Circle`, `Rectangle`, `Triangle`, `Sphere`, `Cylinder`, etc.)
- **Polymorphism** (dynamic method dispatch via overridden methods like `area()` and `perimeter()`)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Highlight:** A package is **NOT** merely a folder. It is a *compile-time and runtime namespace mechanism* that enforces access control, prevents naming collisions, and provides a **modular compilation unit** in languages like **Java** and namespaces in **C++/Python**.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine a large office building (your entire software project) with many rooms. Without organization, you would put files randomly in any room — chaos! 

Now think of a **Shape Package** as a **dedicated "Geometry Department"** within that building:

- The **Department's Reception Desk** = The *package declaration* (`package geometry;`).
- The **Departmental Rules** = The *access modifiers* (`public`, `private`, `protected`).
- The **Departmental Filing System** = The *class hierarchy* (`Shape` → `2DShape` → `Circle`).
- The **Standard Operating Procedures** = The *abstract methods* that every shape *must* implement (`area()`, `perimeter()`).

When a new employee (`Circle` class) joins the Geometry Department, they must follow the department's SOPs (overriding `area()` and `perimeter()`). This is exactly what the Shape Package enforces in code.

### 1.3 Key Terminology (Board-Exam Definitions)

> [!NOTE]
> **Must-Memorize KTU Definitions:**

| Term | Board-Ready Definition |
|------|------------------------|
| **Package** | A grouping of related types providing access protection and namespace management. |
| **Abstract Class** | A class declared with the `abstract` keyword that cannot be instantiated and may contain abstract (unimplemented) methods. |
| **Interface** | A pure abstract type containing only abstract methods (pre-Java 8) and constants. |
| **Inheritance** | The OOP mechanism by which one class (subclass) acquires properties and behavior of another (superclass) using the `extends` keyword. |
| **Method Overriding** | Redefining a superclass method in a subclass with the same signature to provide specific behavior. |
| **Polymorphism** | The ability of a single interface to represent different underlying forms (data types or classes). |

### 1.4 Why KTU Includes This Topic

The Shape Package problem is the **canonical pedagogical vehicle** used by KTU examiners to test:
1. A student's ability to design a **class hierarchy**.
2. Understanding of **abstract classes vs. interfaces**.
3. Practical use of **dynamic polymorphism** (upcasting + method dispatch).
4. Implementation of **mathematical formulas** (area, perimeter, volume) inside OOP constructs.

It is one of the **highest-weightage topics in Module 2** and frequently appears in **ESE (End Semester Examinations)**.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Hierarchical Architecture of a Shape Package

A robust Shape Package in KTU context follows a **two-tier hierarchy**:

**Tier 1: Abstract Layer** → An abstract class `Shape` (or an interface `Shape`) declares the *contract*.

**Tier 2: Concrete Layer** → Concrete classes (`Circle`, `Rectangle`, `Triangle`, `Square`, `Sphere`, `Cylinder`) provide the *implementation*.

### 2.2 Operational Logic — Why and How

**Step 1: Declaring the Package**

The very first line of any Java file belonging to the Shape Package must be:
```java
package shapes;
```

**Why?** This tells the **Java Compiler (javac)** and **JVM** to place the compiled `.class` files inside a directory named `shapes/`. This enforces the *Physical-to-Logical mapping rule*.

**Step 2: Designing the Abstract Class**

The abstract class `Shape` provides:
- **Common attributes** (e.g., `String name`, `String color`).
- **Common concrete methods** (e.g., `getName()`, `toString()`).
- **Abstract methods** (e.g., `abstract double area();`, `abstract double perimeter();`).

**Why abstract?** Because the **formula for computing the area of a circle is fundamentally different** from that of a triangle. You cannot write a single `area()` body that works for all shapes.

**Step 3: Implementing Subclasses**

Each concrete subclass uses the `extends` keyword to inherit from `Shape` and is *forced* to provide implementations of all abstract methods, or else it must itself be declared `abstract`.

**Step 4: Leveraging Polymorphism**

A parent reference (`Shape s;`) can hold any child object (`s = new Circle(5);`). When `s.area()` is called, the **JVM dynamically binds** the call to the correct overridden method at runtime — this is called **Dynamic Method Dispatch**.

### 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Memorize this table verbatim. KTU Part A (3-mark) questions frequently ask for these formulas.**

| Shape | Perimeter / Circumference | Area | Volume (if 3D) |
|-------|---------------------------|------|---------------|
| **Circle** | $P = 2\pi r$ | $A = \pi r^{2}$ | — |
| **Rectangle** | $P = 2(l + w)$ | $A = l \times w$ | — |
| **Square** | $P = 4s$ | $A = s^{2}$ | — |
| **Triangle** | $P = a + b + c$ | $A = \frac{1}{2} \cdot b \cdot h$ | — |
| **Sphere** | — | $A = 4\pi r^{2}$ | $V = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^{3}$ |
| **Cylinder** | — | $A = 2\pi r^{2} + 2\pi r h$ | $V = \pi r^{2} h$ |
| **Cube** | — | $A = 6a^{2}$ | $V = a^{3}$ |

**Where:**
- $r$ = radius
- $l, w$ = length, width
- $s$ = side
- $a, b, c$ = triangle sides
- $b, h$ = triangle base, height
- $a$ = cube edge
- $\pi \approx 3.14159$

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Pitfall Alert:** Many students confuse **Surface Area** with **Cross-sectional Area** for 3D shapes. The formula $A = 2\pi r^{2} + 2\pi r h$ for a cylinder includes *both circular faces and the curved surface*.

### 2.4 Engineering Utility of the Shape Package

The Shape Package pattern is not academic — it powers real-world systems:

- **Computer-Aided Design (CAD) software** (AutoCAD, SolidWorks) — every primitive shape is a class.
- **Game Development Engines** (Unity, Unreal) — collision detection uses abstract shape interfaces.
- **Computer Graphics** (OpenGL, DirectX) — rendering pipelines use polymorphic shape drawers.
- **Robotics & Path Planning** — collision checks use bounding boxes, circles, polygons.
- **Geographical Information Systems (GIS)** — maps are decomposed into vector shapes.

The pattern is the **direct intellectual precursor to the Strategy Design Pattern** and the **Factory Pattern**, both of which are part of the **Gang of Four (GoF) Design Patterns** curriculum in higher semesters.
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Exhaustive Implementation Walkthrough

Below is the **canonical KTU-recommended implementation** of a Shape Package, broken down into multiple files.

---

#### **File 1: `Shape.java` (Abstract Parent Class)**

```java
package shapes;

// Abstract class - cannot be instantiated
public abstract class Shape {
    // Protected data members (accessible to subclasses)
    protected String name;
    protected String color;

    // Parameterized constructor
    public Shape(String name, String color) {
        this.name = name;
        this.color = color;
    }

    // Concrete method
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public String getColor() {
        return color;
    }

    // Abstract methods - subclasses MUST override these
    public abstract double area();
    public abstract double perimeter();

    // toString overridden from Object class
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Shape: " + name + ", Color: " + color;
    }
}
```

**Derivation of Logic (Step-by-Step):**
1. `package shapes;` → places this class in the `shapes` namespace.
2. `abstract` keyword → prevents `new Shape(...)` instantiation.
3. `protected` access → `name` and `color` are accessible in subclasses but hidden from external packages.
4. Abstract methods → force every concrete child to provide its own area/perimeter logic.

---

#### **File 2: `Circle.java` (Concrete Subclass)**

```java
package shapes;

// Subclass of Shape using 'extends'
public class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super("Circle", color);  // calls Shape constructor
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    // Override abstract method - formula derivation below
    @Override
    public double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;  // A = πr²
    }

    @Override
    public double perimeter() {
        return 2 * Math.PI * radius;  // P = 2πr
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return super.toString() + ", Radius: " + radius;
    }
}
```

**Mathematical Derivation of Circle Area:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
A_{\text{circle}} &= \pi \cdot r^{2} \\
\text{Substituting } r &= 5: \\
A &= 3.14159 \times 5 \times 5 \\
A &= 3.14159 \times 25 \\
A &= 78.53975 \text{ square units}
\end{aligned}
$$

---

#### **File 3: `Rectangle.java` (Concrete Subclass)**

```java
package shapes;

public class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double length;
    private double width;

    public Rectangle(String color, double length, double width) {
        super("Rectangle", color);
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return length * width;  // A = l × w
    }

    @Override
    public double perimeter() {
        return 2 * (length + width);  // P = 2(l + w)
    }
}
```

---

#### **File 4: `Triangle.java` (Concrete Subclass)**

```java
package shapes;

public class Triangle extends Shape {
    private double side1, side2, side3;
    private double base, height;

    public Triangle(String color, double s1, double s2, double s3, double b, double h) {
        super("Triangle", color);
        this.side1 = s1;
        this.side2 = s2;
        this.side3 = s3;
        this.base = b;
        this.height = h;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return 0.5 * base * height;  // A = ½ × b × h
    }

    @Override
    public double perimeter() {
        return side1 + side2 + side3;  // P = a + b + c
    }
}
```

**Derivation of Triangle Area using Heron's Formula (Alternative):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
s &= \frac{a + b + c}{2} \\
A &= \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Example:** For $a=3, b=4, c=5$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
s &= \frac{3 + 4 + 5}{2} = 6 \\
A &= \sqrt{6(6-3)(6-4)(6-5)} \\
A &= \sqrt{6 \times 3 \times 2 \times 1} \\
A &= \sqrt{36} = 6 \text{ square units}
\end{aligned}
$$

---

#### **File 5: `ShapeDemo.java` (Driver / Main Class)**

```java
import shapes.Shape;
import shapes.Circle;
import shapes.Rectangle;
import shapes.Triangle;

public class ShapeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Polymorphic array - parent reference holding child objects
        Shape[] shapes = new Shape[3];
        shapes[0] = new Circle("Red", 5.0);
        shapes[1] = new Rectangle("Blue", 4.0, 6.0);
        shapes[2] = new Triangle("Green", 3, 4, 5, 4, 3);

        // Dynamic Method Dispatch in action
        for (Shape s : shapes) {
            System.out.println(s);
            System.out.println("Area: " + s.area());
            System.out.println("Perimeter: " + s.perimeter());
            System.out.println("---");
        }
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**

```
Shape: Circle, Color: Red, Radius: 5.0
Area: 78.53981633974483
Perimeter: 31.41592653589793
---
Shape: Rectangle, Color: Blue, Radius: 0.0
Area: 24.0
Perimeter: 20.0
---
Shape: Triangle, Color: Green, Radius: 0.0
Area: 6.0
Perimeter: 12.0
---
```

### 3.2 Analytical Matrix — Conceptual Comparison

> [!NOTE]
> **This matrix is a favorite KTU Part B (7-mark) question.**

| Feature | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---------|----------------|-----------|
| **Keyword** | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| **Methods** | Abstract + Concrete | Abstract only (pre-Java 8) |
| **Variables** | Instance + Static + Final | Only `public static final` |
| **Inheritance** | Single (`extends`) | Multiple (`implements`) |
| **Constructor** | Yes | No |
| **Access Modifiers** | Any | Implicitly `public` |
| **When to Use** | Shared code + contract | Pure contract definition |

**Decision Rule (for KTU exam):**
- Use **Abstract Class** when subclasses share **common behavior or state**.
- Use **Interface** when unrelated classes need to share a **common capability** (e.g., `Drawable`, `Serializable`).
