## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam - May 2024]**
*Define an abstract class. Why can't we instantiate an abstract class in Java?*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
An abstract class in Java is a class declared with the `abstract` keyword that may contain both abstract (unimplemented) and concrete (implemented) methods. It serves as a blueprint for other classes. We cannot instantiate an abstract class because it may contain abstract methods without a body, leaving the object in an incomplete state. The compiler enforces this restriction to prevent the creation of objects with undefined behavior. For example, `Shape` may declare `abstract double area();` without knowing whether the object is a circle, rectangle, or triangle. **(3 marks)**

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]**
*What is dynamic method dispatch? Explain with reference to the Shape class hierarchy.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
Dynamic method dispatch is the mechanism by which a call to an overridden method is resolved at runtime rather than compile time, based on the actual type of the object, not the reference type. In the Shape hierarchy, if `Shape s = new Circle(5);` is written and `s.area()` is invoked, the JVM checks the actual object type (`Circle`) and invokes `Circle.area()` instead of `Shape.area()`. This is the cornerstone of runtime polymorphism in Java. **(3 marks)**

---

### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

---

**Q3. [KTU University Exam - May 2024] — Choice A**

**(a)** Design a Java package `shapes` containing an abstract class `Shape` with abstract methods `area()` and `perimeter()`. Implement two subclasses `Circle` and `Rectangle` that override these methods appropriately. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

```java
// File: Shape.java
package shapes;

public abstract class Shape {
    protected String name;
    public Shape(String name) { this.name = name; }
    public abstract double area();
    public abstract double perimeter();
}
```

```java
// File: Circle.java
package shapes;

public class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;
    public Circle(double radius) {
        super("Circle");
        this.radius = radius;
    }
    @Override
    public double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
    @Override
    public double perimeter() {
        return 2 * Math.PI * radius;
    }
}
```

```java
// File: Rectangle.java
package shapes;

public class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double length, width;
    public Rectangle(double l, double w) {
        super("Rectangle");
        this.length = l;
        this.width = w;
    }
    @Override
    public double area() { return length * width; }
    @Override
    public double perimeter() { return 2 * (length + width); }
}
```

**Explanation (for marks):**
- Package declaration: **1 mark**
- Abstract class design with proper modifier: **1 mark**
- Circle subclass with formula implementation: **2 marks**
- Rectangle subclass with formula implementation: **2 marks**
- Correct use of `@Override` annotation: **1 mark**

---

**(b)** Write a Java program that uses polymorphism to store Circle and Rectangle objects in a Shape array and computes the total area of all shapes. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

```java
import shapes.Shape;
import shapes.Circle;
import shapes.Rectangle;

public class ShapeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape[] shapes = new Shape[4];
        shapes[0] = new Circle(5.0);
        shapes[1] = new Rectangle(4.0, 6.0);
        shapes[2] = new Circle(3.0);
        shapes[3] = new Rectangle(2.0, 8.0);

        double totalArea = 0;
        for (Shape s : shapes) {
            totalArea += s.area();  // Dynamic method dispatch
            System.out.println(s.name + " Area: " + s.area());
        }
        System.out.println("Total Area = " + totalArea);
    }
}
```

**Numerical Verification (Circle radius=5):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
A_1 &= \pi \times 5^2 = 78.54 \\
A_2 &= 4 \times 6 = 24.00 \\
A_3 &= \pi \times 3^2 = 28.27 \\
A_4 &= 2 \times 8 = 16.00 \\
\text{Total} &= 78.54 + 24.00 + 28.27 + 16.00 = 146.81
\end{aligned}
$$

**Mark Distribution:**
- Polymorphic array creation: **2 marks**
- Enhanced for-loop: **1 mark**
- Method call `s.area()`: **1 mark**
- Variable declaration and accumulation logic: **2 marks**
- Correct output formatting: **1 mark**

---

**Q4. [KTU University Exam - Dec 2023] — Choice B (Alternative)**

**(a)** Explain the differences between an abstract class and an interface in Java. When would you prefer one over the other in designing a Shape package? **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

| Feature | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---------|----------------|-----------|
| Methods | Abstract + Concrete | Abstract (default+static from Java 8) |
| Variables | Any | public static final only |
| Inheritance | Single (extends) | Multiple (implements) |
| Constructor | Allowed | Not allowed |
| Access | Any modifier | Implicitly public |

**When to use in Shape Package:**
- Use **Abstract Class** for `Shape` because all concrete shapes share common attributes (`name`, `color`) and concrete methods (`getName()`, `toString()`). This avoids code duplication.
- Use **Interface** for specialized capabilities like `Drawable`, `Rotatable`, or `Resizable` that may be implemented by shapes from unrelated hierarchies (e.g., a `Sprite` in a game and a `Shape` in CAD both being `Drawable`).

**(b)** Implement a Java interface `Drawable` with a method `draw()` and a class `Square` that extends `Rectangle` and implements `Drawable`. Write the main class to demonstrate. **(7 marks)**

```java
package shapes;

public interface Drawable {
    void draw();
}
```

```java
package shapes;

public class Square extends Rectangle implements Drawable {
    private double side;

    public Square(double side) {
        super(side, side);
        this.side = side;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a Square of side " + side);
    }
}
```

```java
import shapes.Square;
import shapes.Drawable;

public class DrawDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Square sq = new Square(5.0);
        sq.draw();
        System.out.println("Area = " + sq.area());
    }
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout:**
> - **Mistake 1:** Forgetting the `package` declaration on the **first non-comment line**. *Valuation: -1 mark*
> - **Mistake 2:** Using `interface` when the question clearly asks for an abstract class. *Valuation: -2 marks*
> - **Mistake 3:** Not using `@Override` annotation when overriding methods. *Valuation: -1 mark (strict mode)*
> - **Mistake 4:** Confusing **area formula for a circle** as $2\pi r$ (that's the perimeter!). *Valuation: -2 marks*
> - **Mistake 5:** Creating the abstract class methods with a body (curly braces). This is a *compilation error* in Java. *Valuation: -3 marks*
> - **Mistake 6:** Forgetting to import classes from the `shapes` package in the driver class. *Valuation: -1 mark*
> - **Mistake 7:** Declaring the main class inside the `shapes` package — driver classes should be in the **default (unnamed) package**.

---

### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **High-Density Rapid Revision Checklist for KTU 2024 ESE:**

- ☐ A **package** in Java is a **namespace** that organizes classes and interfaces and provides **access protection**.
- ☐ The `package` statement must be the **first statement** in a Java source file (excluding comments).
- ☐ The directory structure must **match** the package name (e.g., `package shapes;` → `shapes/Shape.java`).
- ☐ An **abstract class** is declared with the `abstract` keyword and **cannot be instantiated**.
- ☐ An abstract class **may have zero or more** abstract methods.
- ☐ If a subclass does **not implement all** abstract methods of its parent, it must also be declared `abstract`.
- ☐ Use `extends` for class inheritance (single) and `implements` for interface realization (multiple).
- ☐ **Polymorphism** allows a parent reference to point to a child object: `Shape s = new Circle();`.
- ☐ **Dynamic method dispatch** resolves overridden method calls at **runtime**, not compile time.
- ☐ The `@Override` annotation is **optional but recommended** for code clarity and compiler safety.
- ☐ The `super()` call must be the **first line** in a subclass constructor.
- ☐ `toString()` is inherited from `java.lang.Object` and should be overridden for meaningful string representation.
- ☐ **Circle Area** = $\pi r^2$, **Perimeter** = $2\pi r$.
- ☐ **Rectangle Area** = $l \times w$, **Perimeter** = $2(l+w)$.
- ☐ **Triangle Area** = $\frac{1}{2} b h$ or $\sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}$ (Heron's).
- ☐ **Access Modifiers** order of restrictiveness: `private` < default (package-private) < `protected` < `public`.
- ☐ Compile with `javac -d . *.java` and run with `java ShapeDemo` from the parent directory of the `shapes` folder.
- ☐ The `final` keyword on a class prevents inheritance; on a method, prevents overriding; on a variable, makes it a constant.
- ☐ **Constructor chaining** happens automatically via `super()` if not explicitly written.
- ☐ Always test polymorphic code with **at least 2-3 different concrete shape objects** to prove dynamic dispatch.
